IC:
Decision Scenarios

 

1.     Study Description

You are invited to participate in a research study. We are investigating your decisions in different scenarios. You will receive .5 SONA credits for your participation. The study is being conducted by Eva Wu and Dr. Eric Stone of Wake Forest University.

 

In this study, we will ask you to read 8 short scenarios and answer questions about your decisions. You will also complete a questionnaire after each block of the decision tasks. If you do not wish to participate, please select “I do not agree to participate” below or close your browser window. If you wish to withdraw, you may exit the survey at any time. Any data you have provided to date will be destroyed. Your participation in the study will take no more than 30 minutes.

 

2.     Participation is voluntary

Your participation in this research is voluntary. You may discontinue your participation at any time without penalty by simply closing your browser window. Any responses entered to that point will be deleted. You will still receive full credit for participation even if you skip questions or if you withdraw from the study for any reason. You may choose to not answer any question(s) you do not wish to answer for any reason.

 

3.     Reasonably foreseeable risks or discomforts

The risks from participating in this study are not more than would be encountered in everyday life.

 

4.     Benefits

Although there is no direct benefit to you from your participation in this study, you will be contributing to psychological knowledge. The results from this study may contribute to scholars’ understanding of decision processes.

 

5.     Confidentiality

When completing the survey, please choose a location with adequate privacy and internet security. Please note, however, that while in transmission on the internet, your responses may not be entirely secure. The study team has taken the following precautions to protect the confidentiality of your information. We will not record your identity or any personal identifiers. The data collected will be kept in a secure location. Only authorized people will have access to the research records, and passwords for office computers and networks will be protected. The information in this study will be used only for research purposes and you will not be identified in any publication or presentation from this study.

 

6.     Contact Information

If you have questions or concerns at any time about the study or procedures, you may contact Eva Wu, Department of Psychology, Wake Forest University (email: wux17@wfu.edu), or her advisor, Dr. Eric Stone, Department of Psychology, Wake Forest University (email: estone@wfu.edu). If you have questions about your rights as a research participant, contact the Office of Research and Sponsored Programs (phone: (336)758-5888; email: irb@wfu.edu). Please reference the study number, IRB00024163, in your message. We encourage you to print or save a copy of this page for future reference.

 

7.     Signatures

By selecting the first option below, you indicate that you are willing to participate in this research project and will advance to the survey. If you do not wish to participate, please select the second option or close your browser window.
M1_SeMF: You are playing a poker game. Now, you have two options. One option is to end the game immediately. If you choose this option, you will win $10. Another option is to continue to play the game. If you choose this option, you will win $100 with a chance of 10% or you will win nothing. Which option would you choose for yourself?
M2_SeMF: You are playing a gambling game. You have two options. For one option, you can take a box with $30 in it. For the second option, you would choose among 3 boxes – one of them has $90 in it, and the other two have nothing in them. (You have no way of telling which box has the $90 and which have nothing.) Which option would you choose for yourself?
M3_SeMF: Your bank has announced its end-of-year reward for its members. They offer you two options. In the first option, you could receive a $15 reward, guaranteed. In the second option, you could enter a lottery to have a 25% chance of winning $60. Which option would you choose for yourself?
M4_SeMF: You are at a restaurant having Christmas dinner with your family. As part of their special Christmas promotion, you can choose either to take home $20 guaranteed, or to enter a lottery where one of every five customers will take home $100 (thus you’d have a 20% chance of winning $100, and an 80% chance of winning nothing). Which option would you choose for yourself?
MQ_SeMF_1:
Each of the previous scenarios provided a choice between earning a specific amount of money for certain vs. a gamble with a chance to win more money but the potential to not win anything.

 

While thinking about taking the gamble to potentially win more money, please rate the following: - To what extent did you experience positive feelings associated with taking the gamble?
MQ_SeMF_2:
Each of the previous scenarios provided a choice between earning a specific amount of money for certain vs. a gamble with a chance to win more money but the potential to not win anything.

 

While thinking about taking the gamble to potentially win more money, please rate the following: - To what extent did you experience negative feelings associated with taking the gamble?
S1_SeMF: You have been staying up late the past few days trying to study for your exams. Because of your lack of sleep, it gets harder and harder to get through each day and to stay up later at night. You know that taking caffeine pills can help you stay awake longer. But you also know that caffeine pills are dangerous if misused and are potentially addictive. Which option would you choose for yourself?
S2_SeMF: You are riding alone in a taxi. After riding in the taxi for a while, it becomes apparent to you that the driver is drunk. There are no other taxis around or other means of transportation. Your destination is 5 miles away, and although it is inconvenient, it is safe to walk. Which option would you choose for yourself?
S3_SeMF: You recently moved into a new apartment, which you like except that the living room has nothing in the way of a mantle or shelves on which you can put candles and the various knick-knacks that you have. You order a shelf online to put up in the living room. When it arrives, however, you find out that this shelf is heavier than expected. You put it up, but it doesn’t seem very stable and you're concerned that it might fall down, possibly injure your cat, etc. You could get another one online, since the place from where you ordered allows exchanges, but then you’d have to go through the whole process all over again. Which option would you choose for yourself?
S4_SeMF: You are currently trying to lose weight. You have tried proper dieting and exercise, but the last 15 pounds are just not coming off. You know that taking a diet pill might help boost your metabolism and help you lose the extra weight. But you also know that diet pills can have dangerous side effects and put you at a greater risk for heart disease. Which option would you choose for yourself?
SQ_SeMF_1:
Each of the previous scenarios provided a choice between a safer option and a riskier option that has some advantages associated with it (taking the pill, remaining in the taxi, or leaving the unstable shelf up).  

 

While thinking about taking the riskier option, please rate the following: - To what extent did you experience positive feelings associated with making the riskier choice?
SQ_SeMF_2:
Each of the previous scenarios provided a choice between a safer option and a riskier option that has some advantages associated with it (taking the pill, remaining in the taxi, or leaving the unstable shelf up).  

 

While thinking about taking the riskier option, please rate the following: - To what extent did you experience negative feelings associated with making the riskier choice?
